29 evidence-based instructional practices.
30 (4) It is in the best interest of Alabama's children to
31 ensure that screen-based instruction is developmentally
32 appropriate and grounded in current research.
33 (5) The intent of this act is to promote balanced
34 instructional practices in kindergarten through twelfth grade
35 while preserving local flexibility and elevating educator
36 expertise.
37 (6) This act shall be read in pari materia with The
38 Healthy Early Development and Screen Time Act, Act 2026-169,
39 2026 Regular Session.
40 Section 2. For the purposes of this act, the following
41 terms have the following meanings:
42 (1) BOARD. The State Board of Education.
43 (2) DEPARTMENT. The State Department of Education.
44 (3) SCREEN-BASED INSTRUCTION. The individual use of an
45 electronic device, including, but not limited to, a laptop,
46 Chromebook, or tablet, by a student during instructional time.
47 Section 3. (a) The board shall adopt standards for
48 screen-based instruction for kindergarten through twelfth
49 grade. The standards shall include specific guidance on
50 appropriate screen-based instruction for each grade and shall
51 reflect, but not be limited to, the following requirements:
52 (1) The use of screen-based instruction as
53 developmentally appropriate and supported by research.
54 (2) The use of screen-based instruction only as a
55 supplementary tool for instruction in core academic subjects
56 and may not serve as the primary mode of instruction.
Page 2

and may not serve as the primary mode of instruction.
I3L9BZ6-1 03/12/2026 GP (H) HSE 2026-881
House Education Policy Reported Substitute for
HB584
57 (3) Screen-based instruction may not replace explicit
58 phonics instruction, handwriting, reading of physical texts,
59 manipulative-based mathematics instruction, or teacher-led
60 discussion.
61 (4) Continuous, self-paced digital coursework may not
62 be used as a substitute for teacher-directed instruction.
63 (5) The scheduling of regular vision breaks during
64 screen-based instruction which require students to follow the
65 20-20-20 rule. For the purposes of this subdivision, the
66 "20-20-20 rule" means that every 20 minutes, students must
67 spend at least 20 seconds looking at an object at least 20
68 feet away.
69 (6) Screen-based instruction, including work done in
70 the classroom and assigned to be completed at home, must have
71 clear educational value or involve critical thinking
72 activities, including, but not limited to, coding, immersive
73 simulations, creating multimedia projects, design, interaction
74 with experts, peer collaboration, and research.
75 (7) The exceptions provided in Section 5.
76 (b) Each local board of education shall adopt policies
77 consistent with the board's standards adopted pursuant to
78 subsection (a).
79 (c) The board shall annually prepare a progress report
80 relating to screen-based instruction in kindergarten through
81 twelfth grade. The report shall include, but not be limited
82 to, the use of screen-based instruction in kindergarten
83 through twelfth grade, any revisions to the screen-based
84 instruction standards, and the effect of the screen-based
Page 3

instruction standards, and the effect of the screen-based
